title: For Sale:  Modern Military Modular Integrated Communications Helmet
postcontent:
I am selling a current size Large military MICH Helmet. There is some room to negotiate, but please let's not be insulting because you took lessons from pawn stars, storage wars or you think you're a know it all like the fellas on Duck Dynasty! Send me an email with questions. See the pics for more details. Also don't get mad this is buisness if you get out bidded that's life this is a site to make money and not charity. Wear your big boy/girl panties and deal with it!


The MICH ranges in weight from about 3 lb (1.36 kg) (size medium) to just over 3.6 lb (1.63 kg) (extra large). It uses a new, more advanced type of Kevlar and provides increased protection against handgun rounds.

A pad system and four-point retention system, similar to the cushions and straps found on bicycle helmets, replaces the nylon cord suspension system, sweatband and chinstrap found on the PASGT helmet. The change provides greater impact protection and comfort for the wearer. It can be fitted with a mounting bracket for an AN/PVS-14 monocular night vision device (MNVD) on the front, similar to that on the PASGT helmet. It can also be fitted with a pair of straps on the rear to keep protective eyewear in place, as well as cloth helmet covers in varying camouflage patterns including M81 Woodland, three-color desert, USMC MARPAT, U.S. Army UCP, Crye MultiCam, and solid black for use with SWAT teams. As with its PASGT predecessor, the MICH is often worn with a band around it which features a pair of reflective "cat eyes" -- patches on the back intended to prevent friendly fire incidents.

The MICH is also slightly smaller than the PASGT, providing 8% less coverage. This accounts for some of the reduced weight and allows for both greater situational awareness and less obstruction of the wearer's vision, particularly when combined with Interceptor body armor. Previously, soldiers had complained that the high collar of the Interceptor pushed the back of the helmet forward, in turn moving the helmet brim over their eyes when they attempted to fire from a prone position.

title: For Sale:  Top Quality AK47
postcontent:
A rare Arsenal (Bulgarian) import brought to the USA in it's 100% Bulgarian part configuration.  No pure AK builds like this have come since '99.  This SLR95 has been "re-militarized" by me and brought to 922(r) compliance with 5 US made parts: K-var Warsaw Pact length butt stock, traditional Bulgarian designed K-var pistol grip, and a Tapco G2 double-hook trigger group (3 parts).  The gun also includes the original Bulgarian parts (sporter stock and trigger group) and it's legal to reconfigure it in it's pure Bulgarian state..just doesn't look as cool.  There's a Krebs Custom safety switch that has the bolt-hold-open notch and a edge sticking up so you can operate it while keeping your hand on fire control.  See close-up pic below.

The SLR95 is a milled receiver AK which gives it better rigidity, a more solid barrel/receiver lock-up, and it's more to spec than the stamped receiver AKs.  A milled receiver translates to greater reliability, longevity, and even better accuracy than it's stamped counterparts.  No rivets, a cool lightning cut over the mag well, a more precise magwell (stamped AKs that get imported to the US have all kinds of different magwell fits and are often out of spec).  It's got a very clever brake pinned on that keeps the muzzle down nicely.  This gun shoots much smoother than the Arsenal (Russian) and Bulgarian stamped AK I've had in the past and is much more accurate.  I can bang the 300 yard irons 6 out of 10 times compared to barely hitting it with the stamped AKs I've had.  THis one is sweet.

I've got just under 500 rounds through it (90 put through it today!) without a problem.  It's been cleaned carefully after each shoot (even though it doesn't need it).  I've polished all parts that rub metal (no metal taken off!!) and have only used lithium grease sparingly in a couple spots.

3 weeks ago this gun, used, was worth between $1k-$1200 easily just for it's rarity.  It comes with 7 mags 30 round Bulgarian mags loaded with 7.62x39 ammo (200+ rounds) and the Bulgarian sporter stock, Bulgarian dust cover with the picatinny rail secured to it firmly, and the original Bulgarian trigger group.  With current supply and demand, these good Bulgarian mags are an easy $50 a piece and the ammo a good 40 cents a round adding $430 value to the gun.  In this market, I don't think it's too much to ask $1850 for it all.

FACE TO FACE RAVALLI COUNTY ONLY - CASH OR TRADE (the right 1911 or Benelli M2) - PRICE IS NEGOTIABLE.  Please email me your offer, the worst that can happen is a no or counteroffer.  

VIDEO DEMONSTRATION:   http://youtu.be/M9YtZXFtejU
